  "cap": "SSRF",
  "endpoint": "POST /api/v1/repos/test",
  "rationale": "git_ls_remote_probe feeds the operator-supplied source_url_or_path verbatim to `git ls-remote <url>`. There is no scheme allowlist. `git` recognises far more than https: `file://` reads local trees (info-disclosure pivot — confirm presence of an arbitrary path on the daemon host by watching exit code / line_count), and `http(s)://` resolves with the system resolver, so an attacker who can reach this endpoint can probe internal hosts (cloud metadata 169.254.169.254, corp wiki, internal artefact registries) and learn reachability + response timing from the daemon's network position. The handler is auth-gated, but the bearer can leak through the `?token=` path (router.rs:132) and the surface is then a full server-side request primitive. Static pass missed because the URL never reaches a Rust HTTP client — the SSRF is dispatched by `git`, which the taint tracker treats as a black box.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "POST /api/v1/repos/test {\"source_kind\":\"git\",\"source_url_or_path\":\"http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/\"} — non-zero exit + populated stderr in TestRepoResponse.message confirms the daemon reached the IMDS endpoint."
