{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 759,
  "cap": "INFO_DISCLOSURE",
  "endpoint": "POST /api/v1/repos/test (source_kind=local-path)",
  "rationale": "The local-path branch (router.rs:759-786) constructs `std::path::Path::new(&req.source_url_or_path)` from the JSON body, then differentiates the response three ways: (a) `path … does not exist` (line 764), (b) `path … is not a directory` (line 771), (c) `path readable; on-disk .git/config remote = <url>` (line 778) — the third branch reads `<path>/.git/config` via read_local_git_remote (router.rs:859) and parses the `[remote \"origin\"]` url= line straight into the response body. There is no allowlist confining the path to the configured repos root, no symlink-follow guard, no rejection of absolute paths outside the daemon's working set. Net effect against an attacker holding the bearer (trivially reachable via the leaked-`?token=` paths above): the endpoint is (i) a full filesystem-existence oracle for any path the daemon's uid can stat, and (ii) a content-exfiltration channel for any `.git/config` the daemon's uid can read — including operator home dirs, neighbouring service workdirs, and CI runner checkouts that frequently carry credential helpers / private-repo URLs in the same file. Distinct sink from the git-ls-remote rows: nothing reaches `git` here. Static pass missed because the disclosure is shaped as a deliberate `ok:true` response field (`on_disk_git_remote`), so taint tracking sees a sanctioned data flow, not a leak."
}

