{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent/src/cmd/pr_comment.rs",
  "line": 290,
  "cap": "DOS",
  "endpoint": "<cli:pr-comment build_comment_body — finding.id / chain.id / chain.member_ids[*]>",
  "rationale": "short_id (pr_comment.rs:288-291) slices its &str argument by byte: `let take = id.len().min(12); id[..take].to_string()`. Rust's str-index `[..n]` panics (`byte index N is not a char boundary; it is inside '<codepoint>' (bytes A..B)`) whenever `n` lands mid-codepoint. `short_id` is called four times during render_comment_body (pr_comment.rs:201 row.id, :203 cid, :219 m, :224 chain.id). Every one of those values originates in the report.json the operator hands to `pr-comment --report` — schema_version 1 plus a free-form `id: String`, `chain_id: Option<String>`, and `member_ids: Vec<String>` (scan_report.rs:36-46, :49-54). Findings.id, chain id, and member_ids are persisted in sqlite from candidate_findings rows that the AI Exploration / NovelFinding workers write, so an attacker who lands a single candidate with id like `aaaaaaaaaaa\\u{1F4A3}rest` (11 ASCII + a 4-byte 💣 codepoint that straddles byte 12) walks the renderer into the panic. The `pr-comment` subcommand runs inside the GitHub Action; an unrecovered panic kills the process, the Action step exits non-zero, and the PR comment never lands — the operator sees a CI infrastructure failure with no clear root cause, and any other follow-up step (status check, audit upload) that depended on `pr-comment` succeeding silently no-ops. Worse, build_comment_body is also reachable from cargo unit tests and from any future caller that renders untrusted reports (web UI, CLI `nyx-agent run-card`-style flows). Static pass missed because the panic source is not the canonical `unwrap()` / `expect()` shape — it is a perfectly type-correct slice on a length the developer believed could not span a codepoint. Fix: `id.chars().take(12).collect::<String>()` (Unicode-safe) or `id.get(..take).unwrap_or(id).to_string()` (byte-safe with fallback). Same fix pattern applies to any sibling helper in run_card.rs / report code that slices ids by byte.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "candidate_findings.id = string with 11 ASCII bytes followed by a 4-byte UTF-8 codepoint (e.g. `aaaaaaaaaaa💣rest`); promote -> scan emits report.json with that id; nyx-agent pr-comment --report ... panics in short_id at the .min(12) byte boundary. Reproduce in-process via `cargo test -p nyx-agent -- pr_comment::short_id` with input `\"aaaaaaaaaaa💣\"` (`a` is 1 byte, `💣` is 4 bytes → len=15, take=12 lands inside the 💣)."
}

