  "endpoint": "POST /webhook/git (pre-HMAC body buffering + per-request HMAC-SHA256 over 1 MiB)",
  "rationale": "webhook_git's request pipeline buffers the body BEFORE verifying the signature. Order of operations: (a) header lookup of `X-Hub-Signature-256` at webhook.rs:161 short-circuits a missing header with 401 — cheap; (b) to_bytes(body, MAX_WEBHOOK_BODY_BYTES) at webhook.rs:169 reads up to 1 MiB into memory; (c) verify_signature at webhook.rs:173 computes HmacSha256 over the full buffered body, then constant-time-compares. So an attacker who forges only the header *shape* — any value matching `sha256=<64 hex chars>` is enough to satisfy the parsing in verify_signature (the strip_prefix + hex::decode pair) — pays no secret-knowledge cost yet forces the daemon to allocate up to 1 MiB and run a full HMAC-SHA256 pass per request before the 401 lands. The `/webhook/git` route is always-open (router.rs:115), so the auth_layer bearer gate does not throttle this path. There is no tower::limit::ConcurrencyLimitLayer or per-IP rate limit on the route, no Content-Length sanity check (axum's to_bytes accepts any chunked stream up to the limit), and no Content-Type gate (the handler tolerates non-JSON bodies — `serde_json::from_slice(...).ok()`). Sustained N parallel forged-sig requests at ~1 MiB each saturate the daemon's IO + a tokio worker per request, plus burn ~5–10 ms of CPU per HMAC pass on a modern core — ~100 reqs/s pins one core, ~1000 reqs/s saturates four. Reachability profile: (i) direct TCP from any host that can reach the listener, (ii) cross-origin from a browser — blocked for the *header* path (X-Hub-Signature-256 is a non-CORS-safelisted request header → triggers preflight → daemon has no CorsLayer per the prior CSRF row → preflight fails), but reachable from a DNS-rebound page that switches the resolved IP to 127.0.0.1 after the first navigation (per the existing DNS_REBIND row in this sentinel) because the rebind primitive turns cross-origin into same-origin from the browser's perspective. Distinct from the pass-7 TRIGGER_AMPLIFICATION row (that one