{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-ai/src/adapter/anthropic.rs",
  "line": 236,
  "cap": "BUDGET_BYPASS",
  "rationale": "Cost accounting trusts upstream-supplied token counts verbatim. `cost` (anthropic.rs:236-239) is computed entirely from `parsed.usage.{input_tokens, output_tokens, cache_creation_input_tokens, cache_read_input_tokens}` — fields the Anthropic Messages API returns and the adapter pipes straight into `tracker.add_spend`. There is no client-side sanity bound: nothing checks that `output_tokens` is <= `prompt.max_output_tokens` (the only ceiling the request asked for), nothing checks that `input_tokens` is in the same order of magnitude as `(prompt.system.len() + prompt.user.len()) / 4` (the cost_estimate floor the runtime itself uses at anthropic.rs:320). A compromised, MITM'd, or buggy upstream (or a misbehaving local proxy operators wire in via `with_base_url`) can return `\"usage\": {\"input_tokens\": 0, \"output_tokens\": 0}` on every reply — the cap never trips and the run consumes unlimited real spend at the provider. The mirror attack — over-reporting tokens to drain a competitor's cap — is also unblocked. Static analysis flags neither because the cap-check itself is structurally correct; the trust boundary is the field it depends on. Defence-in-depth applies even when the default base_url points at api.anthropic.com: a MITM with the host's CA trust store can still feed bogus usage rows.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Run the existing wiremock test `one_shot_returns_deterministic_response_through_mock` but return `\"usage\": {\"input_tokens\": 0, \"output_tokens\": 0}` while serving a 10 KB `content[0].text` blob. The adapter posts cost=0 to the tracker, `BudgetTick` records 0 micros, the run can dispatch unbounded follow-up calls against the same cap. Fix: clamp `usage.output_tokens` to `min(reported, prompt.max_output_tokens)` and reject responses where `usage.input_tokens` is more than (say) 10× the `cost_estimate` floor with `AiError::MalformedResponse`."
}

