{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-ai/src/adapter/anthropic.rs",
  "line": 205,
  "cap": "DOS",
  "rationale": "Response body read is unbounded. `let bytes = res.bytes().await` (anthropic.rs:205) buffers the entire upstream response into memory before any size check; the `Client::builder().timeout(Duration::from_secs(60))` on line 113 is a wall-clock cap, not a byte cap, and reqwest does not impose a default body-size limit. A compromised/MITM'd Messages endpoint or a buggy operator-configured proxy returning a multi-GB Transfer-Encoding: chunked body will OOM the agent host (or at least swap it into uselessness for 60 s) before the JSON parser at line 214 ever rejects the payload. Compounding: the same body is then logged into `AiError::UpstreamRefused(format!(\"{} {}\", status, String::from_utf8_lossy(&bytes)))` on the non-success branch (line 207-211), so a hostile 4xx response with a giant body amplifies into a giant error string the rest of the agent has to carry up the stack. Static pass misses because the IO surface is `reqwest::Response::bytes`, not the usual `Read::read_to_end` pattern that body-size lints fire on.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "wiremock `ResponseTemplate::new(200).set_body_bytes(vec![0u8; 2_000_000_000])` — observe RSS spike on the test runner before the JSON parser bails. Fix: switch to `let mut buf = Vec::with_capacity(1<<20); while let Some(chunk) = res.chunk().await? { if buf.len() + chunk.len() > MAX_BODY { return Err(AiError::MalformedResponse(\"response body exceeds N MB\")); } buf.extend_from_slice(&chunk); }` with MAX_BODY sized to the largest plausible Messages response (a few MB)."
}

