  "rationale": "ChainRunner::run (chain_runner.rs:273-280) runs the chain once as `pass0`, then — gated on `self.replay_stable_check` — runs it a second time as `pass1` and stamps `ChainResult.replay_stable = Some(verdict_replay == verdict)`. The contract the docstring (chain_runner.rs:23-27) and the operator-facing doctor banner (main.rs:1801, `report_run`) advertise is that this Boolean answers \"does a fresh re-execution reproduce the verdict\" — i.e. an *independent* second pass. The actual implementation is not independent: `execute_pass` (chain_runner.rs:292-329) only calls `clear_sentinel(&run.workspace, &run.terminal_oracle)?` between passes (line 297), which removes the single sink-probe sentinel file the terminal oracle names — nothing else. Every other side effect pass0 leaves in `run.workspace` (the chain-lane snapshot, NOT a fresh tmpfs scratch) survives into pass1: the per-step synthesised harness files (`nyx_chain_harness_pass0_step{idx}{ext}` at line 347), the per-step inline payload binaries (`nyx_chain_payload_pass0_step{idx}.bin` at line 354 — different names so pass1's writes accumulate alongside, not overwrite), any *workspace-root-relative file* the sandboxed step wrote during pass0 (which is the entire point of running attacker-controlled payloads), any FIFO / unix socket / lock file the harness opens, any compile artefact (e.g. a `__pycache__/` dir, a `.pyc`, a `target/` cargo-cached crate), and — most importantly — any *non-sink-probe-named* file the harness reads back on the second pass. The exact same shape lives in PayloadRunner (payload_runner.rs:182-194 + single_run at :200-244): the in-line comment at payload_runner.rs:226-229 admits the gap directly — `Verifiers that run each payload in a fresh workspace snapshot would not need this, but Phase 19 reuses the workspace.` SandboxOpts at line 237 takes `run.workspace.clone()` straight through. The attack: in any flow where a chain step (or a payload-runner harness, for the PayloadRunner shape) is attacker-influenced — the AiExploration path is one such flow per AttackProvenance::AiExploration (payload.rs:24 / sentinel pass-17 row 17 prompt-injection chain) — the first pass plants any auxiliary file the second pass's verdict observation depends on, *outside* the terminal sentinel that `clear_sentinel` removes. Concrete forgery for the chain runner: pass0's terminal step writes the expected sentinel AND a secondary marker file at e.g. `./.nyx-cache/marker`. clear_sentinel removes the primary sentinel between passes; pass1's terminal step (running the same harness via SandboxOpts on the same workspace) reads `.nyx-cache/marker` already on disk and short-circuits to writing the sentinel again — verdict matches, replay_stable stamps `Some(true)`. The operator UI / promotion pipeline reads replay_stable as the independence claim and promotes the AI-derived Confirmed verdict from quarantine to a high-confidence row (the AttackProvenance::AiExploration path through ChainResult is exactly the path that needs the independence signal to be load-bearing). Symmetrically: pass0 fails at step N and pass1 fails at step N for the same workspace-state reason, ChainVerdict::Inconclusive(ChainStepFailed { which: N }) reproduces verbatim — Inconclusive(which) compared with `verdict_replay == verdict` at line 277 — and replay_stable=Some(true) becomes a confidence stamp on an Inconclusive that was actually a workspace-state-deterministic failure both times. Same shape for the payload runner: pass0's vuln payload writes a marker; pass1's vuln-replay finds the marker already present and `oracle_fired` matches; vuln-replay agrees with the original. Static pass missed because (i) the bug is the absence of a re-snapshot between passes — no sink, no taint flow, no syntactic anomaly to flag, (ii) the in-source comment at payload_runner.rs:226-229 self-documents the gap as a known design choice, so a syntactic-only review reads it as accepted technical debt rather than a soundness claim being violated by the surrounding `replay_stable` contract, (iii) the heuristic novel-pass focuses on shadow APIs / state machines / CORS / business-logic skips — a soundness gap inside a Boolean's contract is none of those categories. Fix: replace the `clear_sentinel(&run.workspace, ...)` call at chain_runner.rs:297 with a workspace re-snapshot — `let scratch = sandbox::workspace::snapshot(&run.workspace_source, &per_pass_scratch)?; <pass uses scratch as the SandboxOpts root>` — and pass that scratch root to SandboxOpts in `run_step`. Same fix in payload_runner.rs::single_run (line 237: replace `run.workspace.clone()` with a per-call scratch snapshot rooted at a per-pass tmpfs path). Belt-and-braces: make `replay_stable_check=true` *imply* the snapshot mode in the runner's constructor so the doctor banner's promise (\"each (vuln, benign) pair re-executes\") is the source of truth and the workspace-reuse shortcut can't reappear in a later refactor. The pass-17 row 23 canonicalise-and-fence on the *snapshot writer* side is orthogonal — that row protects against symlink escapes during snapshot construction; this row needs a *fresh snapshot per pass* regardless of how safe each snapshot's symlink contract is.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Stage a two-step chain with `replay_stable_check=true`. Step 1 spec: a synthesised harness whose body, at runtime, writes a one-byte marker file at `./.nyx-marker` (path NOT named by the terminal Oracle::SinkProbe sentinel — pick anything other than `oracle.sentinel_path`). Step 2 (terminal) spec: a synthesised harness whose body checks `if Path::new(\"./.nyx-marker\").exists() { write_oracle_sentinel() } else { /* nothing */ }`. Run via ChainRunner with replay_stable_check=true. Pass0: step1 writes the marker, step2 sees it, writes sentinel, terminal oracle fires → ChainVerdict::Confirmed. Between passes: clear_sentinel removes the sentinel, leaves the marker. Pass1: step1 writes the marker again (idempotent), step2 sees it (would also see the leftover from pass0), writes sentinel, oracle fires → ChainVerdict::Confirmed again → replay_stable=Some(true). Now mutate step1 to write the marker AND a wall-clock-dependent file; pass0 logs e.g. `1700000000.flag` and pass1 logs `1700000001.flag`. Pass1's step2 still sees the existence of the marker; the soundness gap is invariant. Regression assertion the runner should support: with replay_stable_check=true, an *empty* step1 (no side-effect) followed by step2 that does `Path::new(\"./.nyx-marker\").exists()` should land on ChainVerdict::Inconclusive(ChainStepFailed { which: 1 }) on BOTH passes when run from a fresh snapshot — but lands on Confirmed in pass1 only if state from a prior pass leaked. The same regression covers payload_runner: write a vuln payload whose body is `fs::write(\".sticky\", b\"1\")` and a benign payload that does `fs::write(\".sticky\", b\"0\")`. With the workspace-reuse path, second-pass benign sees `.sticky == 0` (matches), but second-pass vuln on a freshly-snapshot-staged workspace would not see `.sticky` at all and the oracle on `.sticky exists && contents == 1` would NOT fire — exposing the state leak directly."
}

