  "rationale": "main.rs:240 now defaults `config_path` to `nyctos.toml` (was `nyx-agent.toml`). Config::load_or_default (config.rs:380-386) returns `Ok(Self::default())` on `ErrorKind::NotFound` — silent fall-through, no warn, no exit. main.rs:241 stamps `config_present = config_path.exists()` from the *new* path, and main.rs:951-954 feeds that bit into `SetupContext::new(..., config_present, ...)`, which initialises `completed = AtomicBool(config_present)` (state.rs:78-82). So an operator who upgrades to this build with their old `nyx-agent.toml` still on disk and never renamed gets, on next start: (a) `Config::default()` instead of their configured values — `[ai].runtime` reverts to AiRuntime::None (LLM goes dark), `[sandbox].backend` reverts to SandboxBackend::Auto (libkrun / firecracker / birdcage explicit choices silently downgrade to whatever Auto resolves to on the host — frequently Process on macOS dev boxes and on Linux without the kernel module, which is the *least* restrictive backend), `[triggers].webhook_secret_ref` reverts to None (the webhook route returns 503 — the upstream git server retries, observable but not paging), `[[project]]` blocks vanish (the scan subcommand prints `no repositories selected; configure one in nyctos.toml` and exits 1 — operator-visible, but the *serve* subcommand happily continues with no projects), `[ui].listen_addr` reverts to `127.0.0.1:8765` (security-positive when the operator had picked 0.0.0.0, security-neutral on a custom loopback port, operationally bad on a port-collision). (b) `is_complete() == false` re-opens the pre-setup auth-bypass window — auth_layer at router.rs:111-113 grants `/api/v1/setup`, `/api/v1/setup/status`, `/api/v1/setup/doctor` to *any* caller until a fresh `nyctos.toml` is materialised. That is the exact primitive the earlier `record_exploration_finding` row at router.rs:89 / state.rs:78 documented (transient-trust window: anyone reachable on the listener races the operator to POST a SetupRequest with `i_own_this:true`, `sandbox_backend:'process'`, `ai_runtime:'local-llm'`, attacker-controlled `local_llm_url`). The window is bounded on a warm install but UNBOUNDED on every upgraded install that does not also rename the config file on the same maintenance pass. The auth bearer itself survives (auth_token comes from `state_dir.load_or_mint_auth_token()` at main.rs:960, not the config), so the *enforced* parts of the API stay gated — but the wizard endpoints are specifically the ones the bypass arm at router.rs:111 opens, and the very point of that arm is to let the wizard write a fresh config. Even with the bearer in place, the wizard endpoints are reachable without it during the entire post-upgrade window. The secrets keychain service name is hard-coded `nyx-agent` at secrets.rs:35 (`DEFAULT_SERVICE`), so previously-stashed API keys persist across the rename — a SetupRequest the attacker POSTs can reference them by account name (`ai-anthropic`) without ever needing the secret value, so the swap is silent both to the operator and to anyone tailing the keychain access log. Distinct from every prior sentinel row: pass-1 / pass-14 / pass-16 row 2 covers the transient-trust window as a *first-launch* event (one-shot on new installs); pass-21 demonstrates the same window re-opens *on every upgrade* across the rename boundary — a recurring exposure rather than a one-time bootstrap one. Also distinct from pass-13 cli.md CRED_EXPOSURE (that row covers docs advising a non-loopback bind with a TLS terminator the binary cannot provide; this row covers the binary's own config-path migration silently demoting configured-loopback installs into setup-incomplete state). Static pass missed because (i) the source delta is a one-token literal-string change inside a `PathBuf::from`, perfectly benign in isolation; (ii) the dataflow that lifts that string into the trust-window arm crosses three files (main.rs config_path → main.rs config_present → state.rs SetupContext.completed