record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-core/src/report/run_card.rs",
  "line": 406,
  "cap": "XSS",
  "endpoint": "GET /api/v1/runs/:id/summary.md (BySplit.key containing CommonMark blank-line paragraph break)",
  "rationale": "markdown_code (run_card.rs:406-425) computes a backtick fence one longer than the longest backtick run in the input and pads single-tick borders with a space — a correct *fence-length* defence that handles the inline-backtick class of break-out the test `markdown_code_lengthens_fence_to_dodge_inner_backticks` covers. The fix does NOT strip control characters from the wrapped string. Per the CommonMark spec (section 6.1 'Code spans'), a code span is an inline construct and CANNOT span a paragraph break — a blank line (two consecutive newlines, or any whitespace-only line between content lines) ends the paragraph and renders the opening backticks as literal text, with everything after the blank line parsed as a fresh block, including raw HTML if the consumer enabled it. AI-controlled BySplit.key flows from build_run_card's GROUP BY queries: by_cap.key from `findings.cap`, by_origin.key from `findings.finding_origin`, by_lang.key from `payloads.lang`. The pass-11 sentinel row (repro_bundle.rs OS_COMMAND) and pass-13 row (verdict_blob widening) both document that findings.cap / candidate_findings.cap accept any UTF-8 bytes INCLUDING newlines and control chars on insert (store/finding.rs / store/candidate_finding.rs do not validate the cap string). A single candidate_findings row with `cap = \"Harmless\\n\\n<img src=x onerror=alert(document.domain)>\"` promotes (router.rs:1278 path or auto-promote) into a findings row whose cap field is the same poisoned string. The next build_run_card on any run that touches that finding GROUP BYs the cap, builds a BySplit { key: \"Harmless\\n\\n<img...>\", count: N }, hands it to push_markdown_split (run_card.rs:393), which writes `- {markdown_code(\"Harmless\\n\\n<img...>\")}: {N}\\n` to the output. markdown_code emits ``- `Harmless\\n\\n<img src=x onerror=alert(document.domain)>`: 1\\n`` — the source markdown contains a literal blank line inside the backtick fence. A conforming CommonMark renderer (marked, markdown-it, react-markdown, GitHub's own pipeline, pulldown-cmark with raw-html enabled) sees: list item containing a paragraph that starts with an unclosed backtick + 'Harmless', then a blank line that ENDS the list item's paragraph, then a fresh block-level construct '<img src=x onerror=alert(document.domain)>: 1' — under raw-HTML-allowed settings (default for many MD renderers, explicitly opt-in for some), the img tag executes. Under raw-HTML-stripped settings, the renderer still emits a paragraph with the literal text + a stray trailing backtick, but the operator-visible card body is corrupted (extra blocks, misaligned list rendering). Distinct from the pass-2 row that this session's diff was MEANT to fix: pass-2 covered the no-escaping-at-all case; this row covers the partial-fix-bypassed-by-blank-line case. Distinct from every other XSS / MARKDOWN_INJECTION row in this sentinel: pass-3 covers the PR-comment renderer (different writer, different output, render_comment_body uses its own code_safe helper that ALSO lacks the newline-strip — see pass-10 / pr_comment.rs analysis), pass-13 covers the repro-bundle path, pass-23 (this row) covers the run-card markdown that lands inline on the operator's UI. The test `render_markdown_neutralises_injected_html_in_by_split_keys` (run_card.rs:622-647 in the diff) gives a false sense of coverage — it tests `<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>` *without* a newline, the exact case the fix handles. The case the fix misses (newline inside the key) has no negative-test partner. The test predicate `!md.split('`').enumerate().any(|(i, seg)| i % 2 == 0 && seg.contains(\"<img\"))` is itself fooled by the blank-line bypass because the rendered HTML's `<img>` lives in markdown source whose closest enclosing backticks are NOT a code-span (the span is broken by the blank line) but the split-by-backtick check still sees the `<img>` in an odd-indexed segment between two backticks — passes the assertion, ships the row. Static pass missed this for the same reasons pass-2 missed the original: the fix is *type-correct serialisation* with a *fence-length-aware* helper, no missing escape calls remain to flag, the bug lives in CommonMark's semantics rather than in the Rust source. Fix: in markdown_code, after computing fence_len + needs_pad, ALSO reject (or sanitise) any input containing `\\n`, `\\r`, or a Unicode line/paragraph separator: simplest is `let safe = s.chars().map(|c| if c == '\\n' || c == '\\r' { ' ' } else { c }).collect::<String>();` and wrap `safe` instead of `s`. Belt-and-braces: also enforce the same invariant at the writer boundary (store/finding.rs / store/candidate_finding.rs reject newline-bearing cap/rule/origin on upsert), so every downstream renderer — markdown_code here, render_repro_script (pass-11), render_comment_body (pass-3 sibling) — is protected by a single chokepoint.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "1) Stage a candidate finding via the AI-exploration path (this Phase-23 worker's own surface) with `cap = \"sqli\\n\\n<img src=x onerror=alert(document.domain)>\"`. 2) Promote (POST /api/v1/quarantine/<id>/promote OR auto-promote) so findings.cap carries the poisoned string. 3) Trigger a scan whose run touches that finding; GET /api/v1/runs/<run>/summary.md. 4) Save the response, pipe through `pandoc -f gfm -t html5` (raw HTML enabled by default in GFM): observe the img tag rendered as an HTML element in the output, not as inline-code text. Equivalently, view the response in a UI that uses `react-markdown` with `rehype-raw`. 5) Regression test that catches the bypass: extend the test at run_card.rs:622 with `BySplit { key: \"hostile\\n\\n<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>\".to_string(), count: 1 }` and assert that pulldown_cmark::Parser over the rendered body yields ZERO `Event::Html` events containing `<img`. The current test relies on `md.split('`')` which is fooled by the blank-line bypass. 6) Mitigation regression: after applying the proposed `\\n` → ` ` substitution in markdown_code, re-run the same parse-and-assert with the same hostile key — `Event::Html` count stays at zero AND the rendered list item shows `hostile <img src=x onerror=alert(1)>` as literal text inside a single-line code span."
}

