record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-nyx/src/runner.rs",
  "line": 88,
  "cap": "DOS_RESOURCE_EXHAUSTION",
  "endpoint": "<cli:scan> -> NyxRunner::scan() (every per-repo scan; stderr drain on the upstream `nyx` subprocess)",
  "rationale": "NyxRunner::scan (runner.rs:71-117) takes care to keep the child's stdout off the kernel pipe — the file-level docstring (runner.rs:6-8) explains that stdout is redirected to a NamedTempFile via `tmp.reopen()` precisely 'because the JSON output of large repositories can exceed the kernel pipe buffer and deadlock a piped reader.' That reasoning applies symmetrically to stderr; the file claims the opposite ('stderr stays piped because it is bounded'), without any mechanism that actually bounds it. The implementation at lines 86-92 spawns a tokio task whose body is `stderr_pipe.read_to_string(&mut buf).await` — `tokio::io::AsyncReadExt::read_to_string` is read-until-EOF into a heap `String`, with no cap and no early-abort. So a single `nyx scan` invocation against a repository that triggers verbose stderr (one warning per source file in a multi-GB monorepo; a malformed config that emits a hot loop of `WARN`-level lines from the upstream scanner's logger; a benign-but-noisy `--verify` pass against a repo with millions of imports) drives the daemon's resident set up by the full stderr volume, with no ceiling and no operator-visible early-warning until the OOM-killer claims the daemon process. The same shape lives in `read_version` (runner.rs:136-145) via `Command::output().await`: tokio's `Command::output` collects BOTH stdout and stderr to `Vec<u8>` with no cap, so any nyx binary whose `--version` invocation emits unbounded output (a release that accidentally inlined --help, a debug build that prints a banner per loaded plugin, an attacker-controlled `nyx` planted on PATH per the resolve_binary footgun below) OOMs the daemon at discover() time — before the version check even runs. The sandbox abstraction has the right primitive for this — `SandboxOpts.max_output_bytes` (consumed by `read_capped` in backend/process.rs:152-164) clamps both stdout and stderr to a configured ceiling — but the NyxRunner driver is NOT a Sandbox consumer; it spawns `tokio::process::Command` directly (runner.rs:79) and never threads through `max_output_bytes`, so the daemon's own hardening primitive is bypassed precisely on the surface where it would matter (the lane that runs the FIRST process the daemon spawns per scan, and the lane where the spawned binary's behaviour is the LEAST validated). Reachability matrix: today the only caller is lane.rs:51-52, which DOES set `timeout: Some(timeout)` so the runaway is wall-clock-bounded eventually; the OOM still lands before the timeout fires if the stderr arrival rate exceeds the timeout window's deadline-to-OOM margin (cheap to trigger on any host with <8GiB RAM and a chatty scanner). But the public surface is wider than the current call site: `ScanOptions { verify: bool, timeout: Option<Duration> }` with `#[derive(Default)]` means `ScanOptions::default()` yields `timeout: None`; any future caller (a fast-path one-shot CLI subcommand, an embedding harness, a test fixture that forgets the timeout) hits the no-cap path with no wall-clock fallback — `child.wait().await` at runner.rs:103 then waits forever, and the stderr drain task accumulates in parallel until OOM. Adjacent footgun on the same handler: `resolve_binary` (runner.rs:120-134) falls through `which::which(p)` for a non-absolute config_override and `which::which(\"nyx\")` for `None` — both are PATH-driven lookups with no canonical-binary attestation (no checksum pin, no signing check, no `realpath` comparison against an allowlist). The daemon inherits PATH from systemd / launchd / the operator shell; any process-writable directory that lands ahead of the system nyx install (`/usr/local/bin` under a misconfigured umask, a `~/.local/bin` shadow on a multi-user host, a CI runner with a writable scratch dir in PATH) lets an attacker plant a `nyx` binary that the discover() path will (a) execute for --version (instant code execution at daemon startup), (b) accept on any minimum-version string parser shape can mint (e.g., `nyx 999.0.0` from the planted binary's --version stdout), (c) re-execute on every scan with the repo path as a CLI arg. Combined with the unbounded read_to_string sink, the planted binary's --version stderr is the OOM channel; the planted binary's scan invocation is the RCE channel; the daemon's audit trail has NO record that the scanner identity ever changed because runner.rs:46-58 caches `binary: PathBuf` at discover() time but never re-canonicalises, never re-checksums, never compares against a TOFU pin. The 'min_version' string clamp at line 26 (`MINIMUM_NYX_VERSION: &str = \"0.1.0\"`) is operationally cosmetic — the docstring at line 22-25 says 'a configured value below the floor is silently clamped up,' which is the wrong-direction guard (it stops the operator from DOWNGRADING the version requirement; it does nothing about a planted binary OVERSTATING its version). Static pass missed because (i) the unbounded-read sink is `read_to_string` — a perfectly idiomatic tokio API, no syntactic tell, the cap is *absent* rather than wrong; (ii) the comment at line 8 (`stderr stays piped because it is bounded`) is an unjustified assertion the static pass has no contradicting evidence for — the unbounded read is at line 90, two scopes deep, and the comment-vs-code mismatch only resolves when both are read together; (iii) the PATH-based binary discovery is `which::which`, the canonical Rust idiom for binary discovery; the missing canonicalisation / pinning is an integrity claim that is not visible at the source token level; (iv) the OOM lands in the daemon's outer process, not the sandboxed child, so the existing `max_output_bytes` plumbing on the sandbox path does not flag the gap by analogy. Fix options (in priority order): (1) Drain stderr through a capped reader: lift `read_capped` from backend/process.rs:152-164 into a shared utility (sandbox-driver-agnostic) and use it here with a per-call cap (default 1 MiB; configurable via ScanOptions). On overflow, drop the remainder and stamp a `stderr_truncated: bool` field on ScanOutcome so the caller can log it. (2) Apply the same cap to read_version: replace `Command::output().await` with an explicit `spawn` + `read_capped` over both stdout and stderr, with a tight cap (16 KiB is enough for any sane --version output). (3) Bind a default timeout on ScanOptions: change `pub timeout: Option<Duration>` to `pub timeout: Duration` with `Default::default()` returning e.g. 600s; eliminate the `None` arm of the timeout match at lines 94-103, so the no-timeout case is structurally impossible. (4) Harden binary resolution: after `resolve_binary` returns a PathBuf, call `std::fs::canonicalize` and reject any path that escapes a configured nyx-binary-allowlist root (default: `[/usr/bin, /usr/local/bin, $HOME/.cargo/bin]`); persist the canonicalised path + sha256 on first discover() and refuse to re-spawn if either changes across a daemon lifetime. (5) Belt-and-braces: emit a single startup log line `nyx-binary: <canonical-path> sha256=<hash> version=<v>` so an operator tailing the daemon's stderr sees a binary swap on the next restart, and add a `--require-nyx-checksum=<hex>` CLI flag that fails the daemon's startup if the resolved binary's hash does not match.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "1) DoS via verbose stderr: prepare a shim that wraps the real nyx binary: `#!/bin/sh\\nexec >&2; while true; do printf 'WARN: synthetic noise line\\\\n'; done`. Drop at e.g. `/tmp/noisy-nyx`, set `[nyx] binary = \"/tmp/noisy-nyx\"` in the daemon config OR plant on PATH (per the resolve_binary footgun). Trigger any scan from the SPA / `nyx-agent scan` subcommand. Watch the daemon's RSS climb until the OOM-killer fires; confirm the lane.rs timeout (default e.g. 30 min for big repos) is not reached before OOM. 2) PATH-planting RCE: on a multi-user host where `/usr/local/bin` is group-writable for a low-privilege staging account, plant `/usr/local/bin/nyx` ahead of the system install (a wrapper that exec's the real nyx after running attacker payload). Restart the daemon. Observe: (a) NyxRunner::discover() executes the planted binary for --version — attacker payload runs as the daemon user; (b) every subsequent scan re-executes the planted binary with the operator's repo paths as CLI args — full RCE in the daemon's privilege envelope, no audit record of the substitution. 3) read_version OOM at startup: plant a binary at the config-override path whose --version response is `printf 'nyx 1.0.0\\\\n'; yes 'BENIGN PADDING' | head -c 1G` to stdout. NyxRunner::discover()'s `Command::output().await` collects the full GB into a `Vec<u8>` before parse_version() even sees the first line — OOM at daemon startup on any host with bounded RAM. 4) Regression tests: (a) add `runner.rs` test that spawns `sh -c 'yes WARN >&2 & sleep 1; exit 0'` and asserts ScanOutcome.stderr.len() <= configured cap and ScanOutcome.stderr_truncated is true; (b) add test that calls `discover(Some(&planted_path), &min)` where planted_path is `target/debug/test-helpers/bogus-nyx` whose --version returns 1 MiB of output, and asserts NyxError::OutputTooLarge or similar bounded error, NOT a successful discover."
}

