{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-api/src/webhook.rs",
  "line": 199,
  "cap": "DOS",
  "endpoint": "POST /webhook/git (Transfer-Encoding: chunked, no Content-Length)",
  "rationale": "HEAD diff adds a Content-Length pre-check that 413s an oversized advertised body before `to_bytes` runs. This closes the cheap-DOS lane for clients that honestly declare size, but the comment at webhook.rs:192-194 claims `to_bytes enforces the same cap (covering chunked transfer encoding where Content-Length is absent)` — that is the LIMIT enforcement, not an EARLY refuse. An attacker who sends `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` with a well-formed-but-wrong `X-Hub-Signature-256` still forces the server to: (a) buffer up to MAX_WEBHOOK_BODY_BYTES (1 MiB) of attacker bytes into memory, then (b) run HMAC-SHA256 over those bytes, then (c) 401. Per request: ~1 MiB I/O + one 1 MiB HMAC pass, all unauthenticated. Static pass + the existing pass-19 sentinel row (line 426) flagged the pre-HMAC body buffering DOS in general; the diff partially mitigates it but leaves the chunked-TE bypass open. The mitigation gap is invisible to a static rule because the chunked path is the *default* axum body reader — there is no syntactic difference from a normal POST. Fix sketch: refuse `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` on `/webhook/git` (git servers always send Content-Length), or cap the chunked read budget at a much smaller value (e.g. 64 KiB pre-HMAC, with a second-pass body cap once the signature checks out).",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "curl -sS -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8088/webhook/git -H 'X-Hub-Signature-256: sha256=00000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000deadbeef' -H 'Transfer-Encoding: chunked' --data-binary @<(yes A | head -c 1048576) — repeat at concurrency N to measure CPU saturation; compare against a Content-Length: 10485760 baseline (which now returns 413 immediately)."
}


