{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-sandbox/src/bin/nyx_sandbox_shim.rs",
  "line": 65,
  "cap": "SANDBOX_ESCAPE",
  "endpoint": "<sandbox:kill-on-orphan guarantee>",
  "rationale": "The new pre_exec block installs PR_SET_PDEATHSIG=SIGKILL on the sandboxee so a SIGKILL on the shim propagates to its child. The kill path BirdcageSandbox::kill (backend/birdcage.rs:139-145) relies on exactly this guarantee — it calls `state.child.start_kill()` against the SHIM and assumes the sandboxee dies with it. The guarantee is structurally bypassable from inside the sandboxee in three independent ways; any one is enough to leave a sandboxee running after the daemon believes it terminated, which is the scenario the patch claims to close.\n\n  (A) Sandboxee self-clears PDEATHSIG with one syscall. birdcage's seccomp allowlist (birdcage-0.8.1/src/linux/seccomp.rs:264, `libc::SYS_prctl`) permits prctl unconditionally — no arg2 filter, no PR_* opcode restriction. An adversarial payload-under-test (these run inside this very shim via payload_runner / chain_runner) executes `libc::prctl(PR_SET_PDEATHSIG, 0)` early in its main() and the kernel forgets the death-signal forever. From that point the sandboxee is orphan-survivable: kill the shim, sandboxee continues. This defeats the patch's stated guarantee on the *exact* threat model the patch was written for (adversarial sandboxee + operator-initiated kill). Static pass missed because the bypass is a *missing* seccomp arg-filter on a syscall the shim doesn't itself call after pre_exec — there is no tainted flow into a sink, just an absent constraint.\n\n  (B) SUID/SGID/file-capabilities exec target silently clears PDEATHSIG. Per prctl(2) PR_SET_PDEATHSIG: \"The PR_SET_PDEATHSIG setting is cleared for the child of a fork(2). It is also (since Linux 2.4.36 / 2.6.23) cleared upon an execve(2) of a set-user-ID or set-group-ID binary, or a binary that has associated file capabilities.\" The shim does not gate `cfg.program` — `resolve_program` (backend/birdcage.rs:175-189) accepts any absolute path or PATH-resolvable name and the operator's permissions matrix decides what payloads run. A SUID binary anywhere on the host (`/usr/bin/sudo`, `/usr/bin/passwd`, `/usr/bin/newgrp`, `/usr/bin/mount`, `/usr/bin/su`, any pkexec) executed as the sandboxee silently has its PDEATHSIG cleared during execve — the prctl was set in the post-fork pre-exec window but the kernel discards it at the SUID exec boundary. The shim has no programmatic signal that this happened; SandboxOutcome carries no field that says \"PDEATHSIG was clobbered by exec attributes.\" The kill-on-orphan guarantee silently does not apply, identically to (A) but without requiring adversarial cooperation from the sandboxee.\n\n  (C) Fork→prctl race window. pre_exec runs after `fork(2)` and before `execve(2)` in the child. A SIGKILL delivered to the shim during this window leaves the child orphan — PDEATHSIG has not yet been registered. The window is short (microseconds on modern Linux) but non-zero, and the daemon's timeout path is the most likely caller of `kill` near process startup, which is precisely when this window is open. The race-loss probability per kill is small but the failure mode is silent: an orphan sandboxee, not a logged error.\n\n  Cross-platform asymmetry: the `#[cfg(target_os = \"linux\")]` gate means macOS gets zero kill-on-orphan protection. Birdcage runs on both Linux and macOS (backend/birdcage.rs:32 cfg block); the macOS path forks via Seatbelt and has no PDEATHSIG analog. macOS has equivalent primitives (`kqueue` EVFILT_PROC NOTE_EXIT polled by a watcher, or `dispatch_source_create(DISPATCH_SOURCE_TYPE_PROC, …)`), but the patch ships none — every macOS operator stays on the orphan-leak baseline and there is no in-tree comment acknowledging the gap. From a coverage standpoint this is the worst of both worlds: Linux callers may assume the kill-on-orphan story is universal because the shim now \"handles it\", but the macOS half-fix means a chain-lane run that hops between dev-laptop (macOS) and CI (Linux) has DIFFERENT termination semantics on the two surfaces.\n\n  Daemon-side reliance: the daemon kill-path (kill(BirdcageSandbox)) treats `start_kill()` against the shim as sufficient. There is no second-pass enumeration (\"after shim exits, walk /proc and SIGKILL any child whose ppid==1 and whose argv looked like the sandboxee\"). There is no shim-tracked sandboxee-pid the daemon could SIGKILL directly. The whole termination contract hinges on PDEATHSIG holding — and PDEATHSIG is the weakest link in the chain because the sandboxee can flip it off.\n\n  Pairs with: pass-26 (audit-log-injection on shim stderr) — a sandboxee that has cleared its PDEATHSIG can additionally emit forged `nyx-sandbox-shim:` lines to mask the orphan. Pass-24 (NyxRunner binary substitution) — the same orphan-survival primitive lets a PATH-planted payload outlive the shim that spawned it, extending the substitution window past the daemon's intended kill.\n\n  Static pass missed because: (i) pre_exec is unsafe Rust and the rg pattern for taint flow does not cross the fork boundary; (ii) the SUID-clears-PDEATHSIG semantic is a kernel-side rule undocumented in any Rust API surface — no `unsafe { }` block, no `#[must_use]`, no clippy lint flags it; (iii) the seccomp allowlist for SYS_prctl is upstream-third-party (birdcage crate) so a same-repo grep does not surface it; (iv) the macOS asymmetry is the *absence* of a cfg arm, not a present-but-wrong one; (v) the fork→prctl race is invisible to source-level analysis — it requires reasoning about signal-delivery timing across the fork boundary.\n\n  Fix options (priority order, both kill-channel hardening AND policy-attestation):\n  (1) Tighten the birdcage seccomp filter (upstream patch or post-attach `seccomp(SECCOMP_SET_MODE_FILTER, …)` from inside the shim BEFORE Sandbox::spawn): allow `SYS_prctl` only when arg0 ∈ {a known-safe allowlist that excludes PR_SET_PDEATHSIG, PR_SET_NO_NEW_PRIVS, PR_SET_DUMPABLE}. Closes (A) structurally.\n  (2) Don't rely on PDEATHSIG. After `sb.spawn(cmd)` returns the child handle, write the sandboxee pid on a status fd (the FD-3 channel pass-26 already recommended) back to the shim's parent (the daemon). The daemon's kill-path then SIGKILLs the sandboxee directly by pid in addition to the shim, removing the shim from the kill chain. Closes (A), (B), (C), and the macOS asymmetry in one move.\n  (3) Per-spawn process group: in pre_exec, `setpgid(0, 0)` after the prctl so the sandboxee is its own pgrp leader; daemon kills the entire pgrp via `kill(-pgid, SIGKILL)`. Caveat: a sandboxee with SYS_setpgid permitted can leave the pgrp; still closes the SUID and race cases.\n  (4) Linux: drop SUID/SGID/file-caps targets at the shim layer. Before `sb.spawn(cmd)`, `lstat(cfg.program)` and refuse to spawn if S_ISUID | S_ISGID or `getxattr(\"security.capability\")` is set. Closes (B); orthogonal to (A) and (C).\n  (5) macOS: register a kqueue EVFILT_PROC / NOTE_EXIT watcher in the shim that fires on the child exit, and pair with a dispatch source in the daemon that monitors the SHIM's exit — when the shim exits without having published a clean sandboxee-exit record, the daemon `kill -9`s any process whose ppid==1 was forked from the shim within the last N seconds. Coarse but closes the macOS gap without requiring per-process-group tooling.\n  (6) Document the limit. If options (1)-(5) are out of scope this cycle, the comment at lines 51-56 should be extended with: \"This guarantee is bypassable by a sandboxee that calls prctl(PR_SET_PDEATHSIG, 0) and by exec of SUID/SGID binaries; the daemon must independently track the sandboxee pid for kill-path completeness.\" The current comment frames the patch as a complete fix; documenting the residual surface prevents future readers from assuming the kill chain is closed.\n\n  Recommended close: option (2) — out-of-band sandboxee-pid publication on the FD-3 status channel pass-26 already recommended. The same FD subsumes pass-26's audit-log-integrity story AND closes the orphan-kill story; one structural primitive answers two passes' findings. Option (4) is the cheapest defence-in-depth bolt-on for the SUID surface and should land regardless.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "1) SYS_prctl self-clear probe (no allowed hosts required — runs inside the sandbox we already drive): payload-under-test `clear_pdeathsig.rs`:\n```\nfn main() {\n    unsafe { libc::prctl(libc::PR_SET_PDEATHSIG, 0 as libc::c_ulong); }\n    // sleep forever, no signal handler\n    loop { std::thread::sleep(std::time::Duration::from_secs(3600)); }\n}\n```\nDrive via chain_runner with a SandboxOpts that includes `timeout: Duration::from_secs(2)`. After the daemon kill-path fires (timeout-triggered or operator-triggered), inspect `/proc/<pid>/status` for the sandboxee pid recorded in SandboxOutcome metadata — if PPid is `1` (init) and the pid is still alive, the bypass succeeded. Expected today: bypass succeeds, sandboxee orphan-survives. Expected after fix option (1) or (2): sandboxee is killed within the daemon's kill-grace window. 2) SUID-clears-PDEATHSIG probe: configure the operator's permissions matrix to allow `/usr/bin/sudo --version` as the sandboxee program (purely to exercise the SUID exec path; `sudo --version` exits cleanly without privileged action). Actually run a long-lived SUID target on a Linux box where one exists; observe orphan survival after shim kill. Confirm `getpid()` of the orphan and check `/proc/<pid>/status` Pid+PPid lines. 3) Fork→prctl race window probe: instrument pre_exec to `nanosleep(50ms)` BEFORE the prctl call (or pre-load LD_PRELOAD that delays the syscall). From the daemon side, fire `kill(SIGKILL)` against the shim immediately after `Command::spawn` returns; iterate 10_000 times and count orphans. Expected: nonzero orphan count proportional to the artificial delay. 4) macOS regression: on macOS, run any long-lived sandboxee and `kill -9` the shim; confirm sandboxee continues. No fix exists on macOS yet — this is the baseline that option (5) must reduce to zero. 5) Once fix lands: regression test that asserts `prctl(PR_SET_PDEATHSIG, 0)` from inside the sandboxee returns -EPERM (option 1) OR that the daemon's kill-path SIGKILLs the sandboxee pid even when PDEATHSIG has been cleared (option 2)."
}

