record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-sandbox/src/bin/nyx_sandbox_shim.rs",
  "line": 61,
  "cap": "SANDBOX_ESCAPE",
  "endpoint": "<shim:pre_exec PR_SET_PDEATHSIG> + BirdcageSandbox::kill (backend/birdcage.rs:139) lifecycle",
  "rationale": "The new pre_exec hook is a strict improvement on the original silent-reparent behaviour, but it ships with TWO structural gaps that keep the orphan-escape primitive reachable on the cancel/timeout path. Both are platform-shape + ordering bugs, not tainted-flow sinks — exactly the missing-check shape the static pass cannot model.\n\n  (A) Fork-vs-prctl race (Linux): pre_exec runs in the child AFTER the kernel's fork() returned, but BEFORE `prctl(PR_SET_PDEATHSIG, SIGKILL)` executes. The window is short (a single syscall trampoline plus the libc::prctl FFI) but it is non-empty, and the operations that fire `BirdcageSandbox::kill` (timeout reaper at the deadline edge, cancel signal from the daemon's run-cancellation path, an OOM-killer hitting the shim) can land inside that window. When the shim dies during the window, the kernel reparents the partially-spawned child to init (Linux >= 3.4 with `prctl(PR_SET_CHILD_SUBREAPER)` reparents to the nearest subreaper; on a stock daemon process tree that subreaper does not exist, so init/launchd is the inheritor). The child then executes prctl, but `PR_SET_PDEATHSIG` only fires when the *current* parent dies — and the current parent is now PID 1, which never dies. Result: the sandboxee survives the shim kill, the operator's cancel returned `Ok(())`, and the SandboxOutcome shows a successful kill while the grandchild keeps running under the daemon uid with whatever exceptions birdcage already landed.\n\n  Standard mitigation (well-documented PR_SET_PDEATHSIG gotcha): record `original_ppid = getppid()` BEFORE prctl; immediately after prctl, re-check `getppid() == original_ppid` and `exit_immediately()` if not. The pre_exec body as written has neither check. The closure also early-returns `Err(last_os_error())` on prctl failure — correct for the syscall-error case, silent for the race case.\n\n  (B) macOS half-fix (silent platform skew): the surrounding `fn run` is gated `cfg(any(target_os = \"linux\", target_os = \"macos\"))` at line 32, so the same shim binary compiles and runs on macOS. The PR_SET_PDEATHSIG block is gated `cfg(target_os = \"linux\")` at line 57 — there is no macOS counterpart. macOS has no PDEATHSIG equivalent; the closest primitive (`kqueue` `EVFILT_PROC` `NOTE_EXIT` paired with a hand-rolled killer in the child) is non-trivial and absent here. The comment at lines 51-56 reads as a categorical guarantee (\"Make the sandboxee die with the shim\") without flagging the platform asymmetry — and the comment is the only operator-facing documentation of what the kill API promises. Net effect on macOS: `BirdcageSandbox::kill` → `child.start_kill()` (backend/birdcage.rs:142) sends SIGKILL to the shim only; the sandboxee reparents to launchd and continues running. This is the exact pre-diff behaviour the change advertises as fixed. Static review of the diff sees only an addition; the macOS path lost its guarantee not in this diff but in the *commit message and comment* that now claim a guarantee that holds on one OS.\n\n  (C) Inherited gap not closed by this diff (carry-forward, kept here so the close-out covers it): even when PDEATHSIG fires correctly on Linux, it signals ONLY the direct sandboxee. The shim does not call `setsid()` and does not put the sandboxee in its own process group; `BirdcageSandbox::kill` calls `child.start_kill()` which targets the shim's pid, not a process group. A payload-under-test that double-forks a daemon (the canonical orphan-daemon pattern, well-inside the surface of CandidateFinding payloads under chain_runner / payload_runner) detaches the grandchild from the sandboxee before the kill cascade fires. PDEATHSIG SIGKILLs the sandboxee → the grandchild reparents to init → orphan survives. The fix shape is `cmd.process_group(0)` + `killpg(getpgid(shim_pid), SIGKILL)` in the kill path, NOT a child-of-shim signal. Pass-20 (payload_runner workspace reuse) and pass-26 (refused-vec audit-log forgery) both touch adjacent surfaces but do not cover this third facet.\n\n  Combined attack against the cancel path: (1) operator launches a payload-under-test that double-forks a long-lived helper as part of repro; (2) operator cancels or per-run timeout fires; (3) on Linux, PDEATHSIG cascades SIGKILL to the sandboxee — but the helper has already detached, the orphan survives; (4) on macOS, even the direct sandboxee survives, and the helper-or-not distinction is moot. In both cases the daemon's lifecycle view says the run is dead while a sandboxee-spawned process continues to hold any leases the sandbox already granted (file descriptors to allow_write paths, environment variables it read before exec, network sockets if `allow_network: true`). This is the gap that turns the shim's announced \"kill the sandbox\" contract into a probabilistic one.\n\n  Static pass missed because: (i) prctl is the canonical Linux pattern — no taint, no sink shape; (ii) the race window is invisible without a model of `fork() → pre_exec → exec()` timing relative to `BirdcageSandbox::kill`; (iii) the macOS gap is *absence* of a counterpart block, the hardest pattern for syntactic review; (iv) the third facet (process-group kill) sits in the kill PATH, not the diff; static review of the diff alone cannot reach it. (v) the comment self-documents intent in a way that reads as exculpatory — same pattern as pass-20 payload_runner.rs:226-229 and pass-26 lines 73-79.\n\n  Fix options (priority order):\n  (1) Close the race: inside the pre_exec closure, capture `let orig_ppid = libc::getppid();` BEFORE the prctl call, then after prctl re-check `libc::getppid() == orig_ppid` and `libc::_exit(7)` (NOT `std::process::exit` — that runs atexit handlers post-fork, a hard rule violation) if they differ. Cost: two extra getppid calls per spawn, both async-signal-safe.\n  (2) Cover macOS structurally: switch the kill path to `cmd.process_group(0)` (cross-platform via `std::os::unix::process::CommandExt::process_group`, available on both linux and macos targets) and change `BirdcageSandbox::kill` (backend/birdcage.rs:139) to send `killpg(getpgid(shim_pid), SIGKILL)` rather than `child.start_kill()`. This makes the kill atomic across the shim + sandboxee + every descendant in the group, on both OSes, and subsumes the Linux PDEATHSIG addition as defence-in-depth (keep it for the not-killed-by-operator case: shim crash, OOM kill, segfault).\n  (3) Tighten the comment at lines 51-56 to flag the Linux-only scope until (2) lands — the current wording promises a platform-agnostic contract that the gated block does not deliver. Smallest-cost partial fix; does not close the primitive.\n  (4) Add a macOS `kqueue`-based parent-death detector inside the shim's pre_exec / immediate post-exec sandboxee bootstrap (would require a sandboxee-side helper; non-trivial). Lower priority than (2) because (2) already lands the macOS guarantee from a different angle.\n  (5) PDEATHSIG-clearing on setuid exec: orthogonal hardening. `default_system_read_paths()` (backend/birdcage.rs:194) includes /bin /sbin /usr /lib /lib64 — every standard location for setuid binaries (ping, mount, sudo, passwd, su). A payload that execs a setuid binary clears PDEATHSIG kernel-side. Birdcage's landlock layer does NOT block exec of setuid binaries it has granted ExecuteAndRead. Out-of-scope for the diff but worth filing as a future row when the kill contract close-out lands.\n\n  Cross-reference: closing option (2) is the structural close-out the prior passes' carry-forwards have been converging on — pass-20 (workspace reuse), pass-24 (NyxRunner stderr drain + binary attestation), pass-26 (refused-vec audit-log forgery). A process-group-rooted kill path also makes the FD-3 status channel pass-26 fix-option-(2) recommended trivial to wire (the shim already owns FD-3 inside its process group, and child group members cannot squat the parent's FD).",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "1) Race probe (Linux): start a sandbox run, in the daemon issue `BirdcageSandbox::kill` immediately after `spawn` returns (smallest possible delay between spawn and kill). Repeat under load to land inside the fork→prctl window. Inspect: after the kill+wait sequence reports Killed, query the system for any process whose `/proc/<pid>/status` contains `PPid:\\t1` and `Name:` matching the sandboxee program. A persistent hit confirms the race. Repeat with the proposed mitigation (orig_ppid check) and confirm zero hits. 2) macOS probe (macOS host): on macOS, launch a sandbox run whose program is `sleep 600`. Cancel via `BirdcageSandbox::kill`. After cancel returns Ok, `ps -ax | grep 'sleep 600'` — the sandboxee is still running, reparented to launchd. Confirms the macOS gap. 3) Process-group probe (Linux, post-(1)-mitigation): launch a sandbox run whose program is a wrapper that double-forks `sleep 600`. Cancel. PDEATHSIG kills the wrapper; the orphan `sleep 600` survives until 600s elapse — confirms facet (C). 4) Regression test once (2) lands: assert that under all three probes, `ps` shows zero sandboxee-rooted processes after kill+wait returns."
}

