  "cap": "PATH_TRAVERSAL",
  "endpoint": "DELETE /api/v1/projects/:project_id/repos/:name",
  "rationale": "delete_project_repo computes `target = state_repos_dir.join(&name)` and then `std::fs::remove_dir_all(&target)` (router.rs:894-910). `name` is whatever string the operator (or any token-holder) supplied to POST /api/v1/projects/:project_id/repos — and create_project_repo (router.rs:721-765) does *zero* validation: it checks `name.trim().is_empty()`, the source_kind whitelist, and `i_own_this`, then writes the raw `name` straight into `RepoRecord`. A name of `\"../../../../private/etc/nyctos-state\"` (or any other traversal payload) is persisted by upsert, then on DELETE the join collapses through `..` components and `remove_dir_all` wipes whatever directory the daemon UID can reach. Worse: the row-existence check at :877-887 succeeds (the attacker created the row), and the `project_id` cross-check at :883 is satisfied because the attacker owns the project. The recursive delete also drops the on-disk symlink chase (no `is_symlink`/`canonicalize` gate), so a planted symlink under state_repos_dir → `/` gives full FS wipe. Static pass missed because the tainted `name` crosses a SQLite hop (insert→select) before reaching `join`+`remove_dir_all`, and most taint engines drop sensitivity across persistent stores.",
