record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-sandbox/src/payload_runner.rs",
  "line": 466,
  "cap": "VERIFIER_INTEGRITY",
  "endpoint": "shell_literal -> PayloadRunner shell harness invoke",
  "rationale": "Rewritten shell_literal renders payloads as `\"$(printf '%b' '\\NNN...')\"`. Two POSIX-shell behaviors silently corrupt bytes inside the command substitution: (1) `$(...)` strips ALL trailing newlines from its output, so any payload ending in 0x0A or runs of 0x0A is truncated before the harness sees it; (2) sh/bash argv strings cannot embed 0x00, so a payload containing NUL becomes a prefix-only string. Net effect: the verifier's oracle silently runs on a *different* payload than the one whose SHA256 was hashed into agent_traces.verifier_blob (build_verifier_blob in ai_pipeline.rs:1730), producing false-negative VerifyVerdict::Negative for any OS_COMMAND/SQL_QUERY finding whose smallest exploit ends with a newline or contains NUL — exactly the byte classes attackers use to truncate downstream parsers. Static pass missed because the bug is a semantic mismatch between Rust byte fidelity and POSIX command-substitution stripping, not a tainted source. Verifier-integrity attestation breaks: the trace claims `sha256(VULN\\n)` was tested but the shell actually saw `VULN`.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Curated harness with invoke='case @PAYLOAD in *X) : > sentinel.flag ;; esac' and vuln_payload=b\"X\\n\". Expect Confirmed; observe Negative because $() ate the newline so the case label never matches. Mirror test with vuln_payload=b\"X\\x00Y\" — only b\"X\" reaches argv."
}


pass 20 (task=expl-demo): working-tree diff = A migrations/0003_verifier_blob.sql, M store/{trace,schema,mod}.rs (AgentTraceRecord.verifier_blob TEXT, schema bumped 2->3), M report/{run_card,repro_bundle}.rs (test-shim None init), M ai_pipeline.rs (build_verifier_blob hashes vuln/benign payload bytes + spec_id, persist_verifier_trace gains two trailing args, three new unit tests), M sandbox/payload_runner.rs (shell_literal rewrite + new tests). Rows 1-18 from prior passes re-validated against current trees: STAND. Pass-19 row (payload_runner.rs:466 VERIFIER_INTEGRITY) re-validated and empirically corroborated against live shells on the agent host:
- bash 3.2 / dash / /bin/sh all accept `\NNN` octal under `printf '%b'` — portability concern dismissed, encoder decodes uniformly.
- BUT command-substitution byte stripping confirmed on this host: `x="$(printf '%b' '\110\151\012\012')"` -> ${#x}=2 (both trailing 0x0a stripped); `x="$(printf '%b' '\110\000\151')"` -> ${#x}=2 (NUL plus tail truncated to "Hi"). Sentinel-flag harness with vuln_payload ending in 0x0a confirms VerifyVerdict::Negative against a payload whose verifier_blob.vuln_payload_sha256 is the *un-truncated* hash — audit attestation diverges from oracle reality.
