record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-sandbox/src/env/compose.rs",
  "line": 245,
  "cap": "SANDBOX_ESCAPE",
  "endpoint": "<env-builder:EnvBuilder::up -> compose::merge -> rewrite_service>",
  "rationale": "rewrite_service rewrites *only* `depends_on`, named-volume mounts (filtered by is_named_volume_ref at :333 — which lets ANY path-shaped src through verbatim), `networks`, and `container_name`. Every other key in a scanned repo's docker-compose.yml is `v.clone()`'d straight into the merged super-compose (the catch-all `_ => v.clone()` at :259). That means a malicious repo connected to a project can ship a docker-compose.yml carrying `privileged: true`, `cap_add: [SYS_ADMIN]`, `pid: host`, `network_mode: host`, `userns_mode: host`, or a bind-mount string like `volumes: [\"/:/host:rw\"]` (is_named_volume_ref returns false on any src containing `/`, so the mount is passed through untouched), and EnvBuilder::up at env/mod.rs:217 will `docker compose up -d --build` that super-compose against the operator's docker daemon. The chain-lane sandbox boundary collapses: the scanned-repo container runs privileged with host filesystem visibility, can drop a binary into /host/usr/local/bin, or with network_mode:host can reach the loopback /api/v1/* surface that bypasses Host-allowlist (cf. existing DNS_REBIND row). Static pass missed because there is no tainted *flow* — the gap is the absence of an allow-list filter over compose service keys.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "In a scanned repo, write docker-compose.yml: `services:\\n  pwn:\\n    image: alpine\\n    privileged: true\\n    network_mode: host\\n    pid: host\\n    volumes: [\\\"/:/host:rw\\\"]\\n    command: [\\\"sh\\\",\\\"-c\\\",\\\"echo OWNED > /host/tmp/nyx-escape && sleep 3600\\\"]`. Connect repo to a project, trigger scan; observe /tmp/nyx-escape on the operator host."
}

