record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-api/src/webhook.rs",
  "line": 399,
  "cap": "AUTH_BYPASS",
  "endpoint": "POST /webhook/git (dedup poisoned-mutex fail-open)",
  "rationale": "The dedup mutex lock-handling at :394-402 explicitly fails open: on Mutex::lock() returning Err(PoisonError), the handler logs a warning and treats the delivery as fresh. A Mutex is poisoned only by a panic-while-holding-the-guard, and DeliveryDedupCache::record (:161-173) does allocations (HashSet::insert, VecDeque::push_back) that can panic under allocator failure / OOM. Once a single panic poisons the lock, every subsequent webhook delivery — including outright replays — bypasses dedup for the lifetime of the process. The mutex is wrapped in Arc and shared across router rebuilds (per the doc comment at :252), so this is a sticky failure that survives config reload, not a transient race. Combined with the captured-(body,sig) replay primitive in the sibling finding, this turns one allocator hiccup into permanent replay-amplification. Static pass missed because the doc comment defends the choice as 'safe response'; the bug is a state-machine flaw — the safe-default is fail-closed once HMAC has already passed.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Drive the daemon to OOM (parallel /webhook/git with 1 MiB bodies) until one record() panics; then observe that captured-body replays at the new delivery-id no longer get the `already processed` response even when re-using a previously-seen id."
}

