record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-api/src/webhook.rs",
  "line": 162,
  "cap": "DOS",
  "endpoint": "POST /webhook/git (DeliveryDedupCache FIFO eviction lets known-id replays slip through)",
  "rationale": "DeliveryDedupCache::record is documented as `LRU-ish` (:144) but the implementation is strict-FIFO: on a cache hit (:162-164) the existing id is NOT moved to the back of `order`, so the eviction order is purely arrival order. An attacker who has the shared secret (or who only needs replayability of a captured legitimate signature — see the sibling delivery-id-forgery row) can flush any target delivery-id out of the 1024-entry window by sending 1024 fresh deliveries; the originally-seen id rolls off the front, and the captured (body,sig) replay under that *same* delivery-id is then accepted as fresh. The cap has no time-decay either, so the cache holds 1024 entries until the process restarts — making the eviction window cheap to engineer. Static pass missed because the bug is a divergence between the doc comment and the FIFO `pop_front()` at :166, not a tainted flow.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Replay 1024 distinct delivery-ids (any fresh UUID each) under valid (body, sig) — observe that the 1025th replay under the *original* captured id re-fires the scan because the dedup entry was evicted FIFO."
}

