record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-sandbox/src/env/mod.rs",
  "line": 268,
  "cap": "SANDBOX_COLLISION",
  "endpoint": "<env-builder:EnvBuilder::refuse_if_project_in_use -> names.iter().any(n == self.project_name)>",
  "rationale": "The new project-name collision gate at :251-271 reads `docker compose ls --all --format json` (which returns names *as docker normalized them*: lowercased, with any of `.` / space / unicode separator / etc. collapsed per docker compose's project-name normalization rules) and compares each entry to `self.project_name` with raw string equality. `self.project_name` is `Project::name.clone()` taken verbatim from operator config (nyx-agent-core/src/project/mod.rs:35 — free-form String, no validator). So whenever the operator's `Project::name` is anything other than already-canonical (uppercase letters, embedded spaces, leading/trailing whitespace, or chars docker strips), the filter at :268 returns false on a *true* collision: docker shows the running project as `myproj`, our config holds `MyProj`, comparison fails, the gate waves the spin through, and `docker compose --project-name MyProj up -d --build` resolves to the same `myproj` namespace docker already runs — adopting another builder's containers, with `RunningEnv::down` later tearing both down. The gate's stated job per the doc-comment is exactly this scenario, so the bug is the canonicalization gap, not the gate's presence. Static pass missed because there is no tainted flow — both inputs to the `==` are *trusted*; the defect is the mismatch between docker's normalization and Rust's `String::eq`. Closes once the comparison normalizes both sides (lowercase + sanitise_filename-style char filter) or the gate switches to comparing on the docker-side normalized form before `up`.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Operator A configures project `name = \"Demo-App\"`. EnvBuilder::up runs, docker creates compose project `demo-app`. Operator B configures `name = \"demo-app\"` (or pid-recycle path picks the lowercased form via a different code path) and runs EnvBuilder::up: refuse_if_project_in_use sees docker's `demo-app`, compares against `demo-app`, refuses. Now flip: A starts second, sees docker's `demo-app`, compares against `Demo-App` — mismatch, gate passes, second `up` lands on the same namespace; either builder's `down` tears down both."
}

