{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-sandbox/src/env/mod.rs",
  "line": 218,
  "cap": "SANDBOX_ESCAPE",
  "endpoint": "<env-builder:EnvBuilder::up orphan-adoption TOCTOU>",
  "rationale": "Two compounding gaps in the new collision gate. (1) TOCTOU: refuse_if_project_in_use issues `docker compose ls` at :215, then EnvBuilder::up runs `compose up -d --build` at :218 with no atomic claim in between — there is no lock file, no advisory `docker compose create --no-start` to reserve the project, no retry of the ls after up. A co-tenant on the docker socket (anyone in the `docker` group, or any other process the operator runs) can win the gap by issuing `docker run -l com.docker.compose.project=<our_name> -l com.docker.compose.service=pwn --privileged --net=host --pid=host -v /:/host:rw alpine sleep infinity` between our ls and our up. (2) Missing --remove-orphans on up: `cmd.arg(\"up\").arg(\"-d\").arg(\"--build\")` at :218 omits --remove-orphans, so any container carrying matching compose labels but unknown to our super-compose survives the up (compose 2.x warns but keeps orphans by default). The pre-injected attacker container is then part of OUR project for the lifetime of the scan: it shares the compose-created default network with the scanned services, can ARP-spoof and intercept their traffic, and runs privileged on the operator host. Note the existing rewrite_service-passthrough row already buys SANDBOX_ESCAPE via a malicious *repo* compose; this new row buys the same primitive without needing a malicious repo, only docker-socket-adjacent co-tenancy and a predictable project name (`nyx-env-<pid>` per the doc comment at :211). RunningEnv::down at :356 uses `--remove-orphans --volumes`, which now also wipes any genuine adjacent operator workloads that happened to label-collide — turning the asymmetry into a co-tenant DOS primitive on teardown. Static pass missed because the gap is a missing CLI flag (--remove-orphans) plus an absent atomicity guarantee, neither of which is a tainted flow.",
