  "endpoint": "<cli:pr-comment --gh-api>",
  "rationale": "validate_gh_api_url at :329-379 enforces the IMDS / link-local block list by string-prefix match on a lowercased host token (`host_lc.starts_with(\"169.254.\")` at :371, `host_lc.starts_with(\"fe80:\")` at :374, `METADATA_HOSTS` equality at :366-369). reqwest then passes the host through libresolv / system DNS, which accepts (a) decimal integer IPv4 like `2852039166`, (b) hex like `0xa9fea9fe`, (c) octal like `024777724776`, (d) IPv4-mapped IPv6 like `[::ffff:169.254.169.254]` or `[0:0:0:0:0:ffff:a9fe:a9fe]`, (e) any attacker-controlled DNS name that resolves to 169.254.169.254. None of those forms start with the literal `169.254.` prefix or appear in METADATA_HOSTS, so they pass the guard while still hitting the EC2 / OpenStack IMDS endpoint. The default GitHub bearer header (build_client at :395-409, set_sensitive notwithstanding) is attached to every subsequent request, so a single accepted --gh-api leaks $GITHUB_TOKEN to the metadata endpoint (which on EC2 redirects credential responses to whoever asked). Trust boundary breaks under pull_request_target flows that interpolate fork-controlled YAML into the --gh-api argument; the comment at :318-323 already names that scenario. Static pass missed this because the prefix-string check looks defensive on its face; the bypass needs knowledge of host-token parsing rules that diverge between the validator and the resolver.",
