  "rationale": "When the detached reaper's `docker compose down --volumes --remove-orphans` does not complete inside DOWN_TIMEOUT (60s), the code at mod.rs:432-433 calls `child.kill()` followed by `child.wait()`. `Child::kill()` on Unix sends SIGKILL (Tokio uses SIGKILL even though std::process documents 'platform-specific' — confirmed at https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/process/struct.Child.html#method.kill: 'kills... by sending SIGKILL on Unix and TerminateProcess on Windows', and the std impl maps to SIGKILL via `kill(pid, SIGKILL)`). `docker compose down --volumes` is a multi-step operation: (1) stop services, (2) remove containers, (3) remove networks, (4) remove named volumes whose lifecycle is bound to the compose project. Steps 3-4 are network/storage-driver-bound and can each take 10-30s on a busy host. SIGKILL during step 3 leaves the compose-project networks attached to (now-removed) containers; on the Docker engine side they show as 'in use by stopped containers' and a subsequent `docker compose up` for the same project name errors with `Error response from daemon: network nyx-env-foo_default is already in use by container <hash>`. SIGKILL during step 4 leaves named volumes orphaned (still labelled `com.docker.compose.project=nyx-env-foo`) but no longer in `docker compose ls`, so `docker compose ls --format json` does NOT report the project as still-running — `refuse_if_project_in_use` (mod.rs:254-272) sees the project absent and returns Ok, the next EnvBuilder::up runs, `docker compose up` creates new containers under the same project name, and they pick up the *old* orphan volumes and networks (docker compose binds volumes by `<project>_<service>` name, deterministic across runs). The cross-run state contamination is the exact threat the threat-model comment at mod.rs:14-19 was meant to prevent (`'prevent an operator from accidentally pointing a sandboxed scan at production credentials' — fail-closed`). Concrete impact path: (a) scan-1 starts under operat