exiting (it traps the signal and runs cleanup). (2) after any timeout-then-kill path, re-run `docker compose down --volumes --remove-orphans` once more from the same reaper thread (without timeout) so the orphans get cleared on the retry; only after that second run errs do we accept leak. (3) in `refuse_if_project_in_use`, also `docker volume ls --filter label=com.docker.compose.project=<name>` and `docker network ls --filter label=com.docker.compose.project=<name>` and refuse with `EnvError::ProjectInUse` when ANY of the three are non-empty — catches the orphan-volume case the current `compose ls` alone misses. (4) bump DOWN_TIMEOUT from 60s to a value that empirically captures the 99th-percentile down-time on a loaded host (3-5 minutes is reasonable for projects with many volumes), with a config-file override for operators on slow storage.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "controlled repro: (1) seed a compose project whose `services.X.volumes` list references 5+ named volumes mounted on a slow disk (loopback ext4 image throttled via cgroup io.bfq.weight=10, or simply on a docker-machine remote with high RTT). (2) EnvBuilder::up the project. (3) on the host, suspend the docker daemon for >60s (`docker pause` on the docker-CLI's own container if running docker-in-docker; or `kill -STOP $(pgrep dockerd)` and resume after 65s on a Linux host). (4) drop the RunningEnv inside this window. (5) after `kill -CONT $(pgrep dockerd)`, observe `docker volume ls --filter label=com.docker.compose.project=nyx-env-<name>` reports volumes the project no longer references AND `docker compose ls` reports the project absent. (6) re-run `EnvBuilder::up` with the same project name; observe the new containers inherit the orphaned volume contents (verify by writing a marker file to the volume in scan-1, reading it in scan-2). Regression test once fix lands: assert that after a forced timeout-then-kill path, a final synchronous `docker compose down --volumes --remove-orphans` re-run from the reaper drains the orphans and `docker volume ls --filter label=com.docker.compose.project=<name>` returns zero rows."
}

notes (pass 24):
- both rows sit on the SAME diff hunks as pass-23 rows but target distinct failure modes. The wildcard-allowlist row (pass-23 AUTH_BYPASS) is about the *guard* fail-open; the DOS row above is about the *cleanup spawn* exhaustion under burst; the SIGKILL row is about the *cleanup completion* leaving partial state across runs. All three are independent fixes — landing any one does not close the others.
- the DOS row chains with the prior pass-1 CSRF row, pass-9 pre-HMAC webhook DoS row, and pass-7 scheduler cross-project row to give a remote-driven thread-storm primitive. Closing the spawn semaphore (fix option 2 above — runtime-owned teardown queue) closes the row from the sink side regardless of how many triggers reach it from upstream.
- the SIGKILL row pairs with the pass-23 secrets-race row: both want the reaper to behave more like an orderly graceful-shutdown, less like a 'fire-and-forget then SIGKILL' detached thread. A single fix that escalates SIGTERM → poll → SIGKILL + retry (and re-stats secrets_path before passing it) closes both half-failures.
- pass-23 carry-forward triggers (xxv) and (xxvi) for the allowlist + Drop fixes are extended:
    (xxvii) any addition of a spawn semaphore / runtime-owned teardown queue that bounds concurrent reapers closes the pass-24 DOS row;
    (xxviii) any change to the Drop SIGKILL path that escalates SIGTERM → poll → SIGKILL with a retry of `docker compose down --volumes --remove-orphans` on the timeout path closes the pass-24 RESOURCE_LEAK row from the sink side; alternatively widening `refuse_if_project_in_use` to also reject leftover volumes / networks closes it from the next-up side.
- no http.probe issued (ALLOWED HOSTS empty), no shell.exec, no fs writes outside this sentinel.
- tool budget this pass: ~9 / 24 calls. Stops here per quality-over-count.



