record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/webhook.rs",
  "line": 360,
  "cap": "TRIGGER_CONFUSION",
  "endpoint": "POST /webhook/git (webhook_provider='bitbucket')",
  "rationale": "BitbucketServerExtractor reads `changes[0].refId` only — no inspection of `changes[0].type` and no fan-out across additional `changes[]` entries. Bitbucket Server emits `type: \"UPDATE\" | \"ADD\" | \"DELETE\"`. A push that *deletes* a branch (type='DELETE') still yields a parseable `refs/heads/<branch>` refId, so the dispatcher treats the deletion as a trigger and kicks a scan against a branch that no longer exists upstream — the resulting clone fails, but the trigger spent its dedup slot and a run row, masking real follow-up pushes that hit the same delivery-id dedup window. Worse: a batched push with `changes=[delete branch X, push to branch Y]` only ever sees X. Combined with `webhook_branch` allow-list semantics (an exact-string match at handler scope, not provider scope), an upstream that deletes a stale `main` branch on the same commit that pushes to a feature branch will trigger a scan-on-deleted-main and silently drop the real push. State-machine flaw the static pass cannot model — no taint, just missing typeflag validation + array head-only read.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "POST a Bitbucket Server webhook body `{\"changes\":[{\"refId\":\"refs/heads/main\",\"type\":\"DELETE\"},{\"refId\":\"refs/heads/feat\",\"type\":\"UPDATE\"}]}` and observe a triggered run against deleted `main` plus zero run for `feat`."
}

