{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent/src/cmd/pr_comment.rs",
  "line": 366,
  "cap": "SSRF",
  "endpoint": "pr-comment --gh-api <URL> (forwards GITHUB_TOKEN Bearer to host)",
  "rationale": "validate_gh_api_url's IMDS guard does string-compare on the raw authority literal (`host_lc == \"169.254.169.254\"` and `host_lc.starts_with(\"169.254.\")`), but reqwest delegates to the `url` crate which normalises non-canonical IPv4 forms — decimal (`2852039166`), hex (`0xa9.0xfe.0xa9.0xfe`), octal (`0251.0376.0251.0376`), shorthand (`169.254.43518`), and zero-padded (`169.254.0169.0254`) — into 169.254.169.254 *after* validate_gh_api_url returns Ok. The check at :371 also misses `0.0.0.0` (kernel routes to a local listener on Linux) and IPv4-mapped IPv6 (`https://[::ffff:a9fe:a9fe]/`) which reach the IMDS endpoint over IPv6 dualstack on many cloud hosts. Trust boundary: `pull_request_target` workflows interpolate forked-PR inputs into the `--gh-api` flag, so the attacker controls the URL while the runner attaches `Authorization: Bearer $GITHUB_TOKEN` (build_client:401) and ships it on the first GET. Static pass missed because the bug is a parser-mismatch (validator sees raw string; transport sees normalised host), not a tainted flow — every sink is already authenticated, every URL is operator-supplied.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "gh-api='https://2852039166/latest/api-token' (decimal IMDS) or 'https://[::ffff:a9fe:a9fe]/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/' from a forked PR's title via pull_request_target interpolation — observe GITHUB_TOKEN in the IMDS access log."
}

